From Doc
&gt; A web application can define any number of DispatcherServlets. Each servlet will operate in its own namespace, loading its own application context with mappings, handlers, etc. Only the root application context as loaded by ContextLoaderListener, if any, will be shared.

## Advantages of multiple dispatcher servlets &lt;sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt; OR &lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; Why we need multiple dispatcher servlets?

*Simple answer is to have [DispatcherServlet&#39;s][1] functionality in several forms*&lt;br&gt;

## Dispatcher servlet functionality&lt;br&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;

- Dispatcher Servlet uses [HandlerMapping][2] implementation to control the routing of requests to handler objects. Default is [BeanNameUrlHandlerMapping][3] and [RequestMappingHandlerMapping][4]. 
- It&#39;s view resolution strategy can be specified via a [ViewResolver][5] implementation, resolving symbolic view names into View objects. Default is [InternalResourceViewResolver][6]. 
- It&#39;s exception resolution strategy can be specified via a [HandlerExceptionResolver][7], for example mapping certain exceptions to error pages.
- It&#39;s strategy for resolving multipart requests is determined by a [MultipartResolver][8] implementation.
- It&#39;s locale resolution strategy is determined by a [LocaleResolver][9].
- It&#39;s theme resolution strategy is determined by a [ThemeResolver][10].

&lt;hr&gt;
I will try to explain some of the functionalities provided by `DispatcherServlet`&lt;br&gt;

**Declaring Multiple dispatcher servlets**&lt;br&gt;
Consider we have two dispatcher servlets(DS) where DS1, DS2 are configured with different url patterns(`**.simple, **.beanName`) and they uses different dispatcher servlet configuration provided as given below.
```xml
DispatcherServlet     - simpleUrlHandlerDispatcherServlet
contextConfigLocation - /WEB-INF/simpleUrlHandlerMapping.xml
&lt;url-pattern&gt;*.simple&lt;/url-pattern&gt;

DispatcherServlet     - beanNameUrlHandlerDispatcherServlet
contextConfigLocation - /WEB-INF/beanNameUrlHandlerMapping.xml
&lt;url-pattern&gt;*.beanName&lt;/url-pattern&gt;
```

**&lt;sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;Advantage 1:&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; We can have different HandlerMapping for different set of URL**&lt;br&gt;

 *DS1 bean name url handler mapping configuration*&lt;br&gt;
```xml
&lt;bean name=&quot;/hello.beanName&quot; class=&quot;com.pvn.mvc.HelloController&quot; /&gt;
&lt;bean name=&quot;/hi.beanName&quot; class=&quot;com.pvn.mvc.HiController&quot; /&gt;
```
 *DS2 simple url handler mapping configuration*&lt;br&gt;
```xml
&lt;bean class=&quot;org.springframework.web.servlet.handler.SimpleUrlHandlerMapping&quot;&gt;
	&lt;property name=&quot;mappings&quot;&gt;
		&lt;props&gt;
			&lt;prop key=&quot;/hello.simple&quot;&gt;simpleHello&lt;/prop&gt;
			&lt;prop key=&quot;/hi.simple&quot;&gt;simpleHi&lt;/prop&gt;
		&lt;/props&gt;
	&lt;/property&gt;
&lt;/bean&gt;
```

**&lt;sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;Advantage 2:&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; We can have different view resolver for different set of URL&#39;s.**&lt;br&gt;

**InternalResourceViewResolver** for DS1&lt;br&gt;
where it deals with only `prefix + returned String + suffix`.&lt;br&gt;
**[TilesViewResolver][11]** for DS2&lt;br&gt;
its implementation provided by apache tiles which is a layout/skeleton based plugin high level functionality as given below.&lt;br&gt;
[![enter image description here][12]][12]
Or if we use TilesViewResolver with different layout for different set of URL&#39;s&lt;br&gt;
anonymous user - different layout&lt;br&gt;
logged in user - different layout&lt;br&gt;

**&lt;sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;Advantage 3:&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; We can have different theme resolver for different set of URL&#39;s.**&lt;br&gt;
These resolver continuously monitors cookie/session to resolve theme and serves stylesheet/theme qualified (as given in below image). Below given just an example for outcome of [CookieThemeResolver][15].&lt;br&gt;
Note: This is not about theme configuration but about theme resolver configuration.

[![enter image description here][13]][13]

**&lt;sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;Advantage 4:&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; We can have different locale resolver for different set of URL&#39;s.**&lt;br&gt;
These resolver continuously monitors cookie/session/accept-header to resolve locale and loads application message qualified(as given in below image). Below given just an example for outcome of [CookieLocaleResolver][16].&lt;br&gt;
Note: This is not about locale configuration but about locale resolver configuration.&lt;br&gt;
[![enter image description here][14]][14]


  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/DispatcherServlet.html
  [2]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/HandlerMapping.html
  [3]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/handler/BeanNameUrlHandlerMapping.html
  [4]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/mvc/method/annotation/RequestMappingHandlerMapping.html
  [5]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/ViewResolver.html
  [6]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/view/InternalResourceViewResolver.html
  [7]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/HandlerExceptionResolver.html
  [8]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/multipart/MultipartResolver.html
  [9]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/LocaleResolver.html
  [10]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/ThemeResolver.html
  [11]: https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/view/tiles3/TilesViewResolver.html
